* **IV. Tenant Responsibilities**  
* **V. Responsibilities of Rental Property Owners and Managers**  
* **VI. Licensed Pest Control Operators (PCOs)**

All language has been updated for clarity (approx. 7th‑grade reading level), and all program names/phone numbers have been updated to **Healthy Housing and Vector Control – 415‑252‑3800**.

# III. Regulatory Authority (Rewritten Version)

**Article 11, Section 581(a)** of the San Francisco Health Code states that no person may allow any public nuisance to exist on any premises or real property owned, occupied, or controlled by that person.

**Section 581(b) (1–15)** identifies the following conditions as public health nuisances:

1. Any accumulation of filth, garbage, unsanitary debris, or waste material.  
2. Any accumulation of hay, grass, straw, weeds, or overgrown vegetation.  
3. Any buildings, structures, or portions of buildings determined to be unsanitary.  
4. Any matter or material that consists of, or is contaminated by, animal or human excrement, urine, or other biological fluids.  
5. Any past harborages or infestations, including but not limited to those involving pigeons, skunks, raccoons, opossums, or snakes. (Exception: pigeon coops that comply with applicable requirements.)  
6. Any noxious insect harborages or infestations, including but not limited to cockroaches, fleas, scabies, lice, spiders or other arachnids, houseflies, wasps, and mosquitoes. (Exceptions apply for honey‑producing bee harborages.)  
7. Any violation of Article 2, Section 92, including requirements intended to protect public health and prevent the spread of rodent‑borne disease.

**Section 92(b)** — **Buildings Required To Be Free of Rodents**

All buildings, places, and premises within the City and County of San Francisco must be kept continuously clean and sanitary, and must be maintained free of rodents by the owner and/or occupant.

**Section 92(c)** — **Exclusion of Rodents in Buildings**

All buildings and the basement walls of storerooms, warehouses, residences, or other structures containing food, goods, wares, or merchandise that may attract rodents must be maintained in a condition that prevents rodent infestation. Owners or occupants must take all necessary steps to prevent rodents from entering or accessing these areas.

**15\.** Any other condition the Director determines to be a threat to public health or safety.

### Section 596\. Enforcement

Section 596 outlines the complaint, notice, hearing, order, abatement, and legal procedures used to enforce Section 581\.

### References

To view the full text of the San Francisco Health Code sections referenced above, visit:

[http://www.sfdph.org/eh/laws/Index.htm](http://www.sfdph.org/eh/laws/Index.htm)

Additional applicable laws include:

* California Civil Code Section 1941.1  
* California Health and Safety Code Section 17920.3  
* California Retail Food Code Section 114259.1: Food facilities must be free of vermin  
* California Retail Food Code Section 114245: Garbage facilities must be properly maintained

# IV. RESPONSIBILITIES OF TENANTS

**1\. Housekeeping**

Tenants must keep their homes **reasonably clean and orderly**. This includes storing garbage correctly, keeping food covered, and avoiding clutter that can attract pests. Tenants must not feed wildlife or pigeons.

**2\. Reporting Problems Early**

Tenants must report any signs of pests in their unit or shared areas as soon as possible. DPH and the Rent Board recommend that tenants submit complaints **in writing** and keep a copy for their records.

**3\. Cooperation**

Tenants must cooperate with building managers and pest control companies. This includes allowing reasonable access for inspections and treatments.

**4\. Preparing for Treatment**

Tenants must follow instructions from pest control operators to prepare their unit for treatment.

**5\. Cleaning and Removing Clutter**

Tenants must remove unnecessary items and store belongings in an organized way to make inspections and treatments effective.

**6\. Meetings or Notices**

DPH may issue a Notice of Violation or schedule a meeting with tenants who do not cooperate or who create conditions that allow pests to live or spread. If needed, DPH may declare a unit a **public health nuisance**.

**7\. When Management Doesn’t Respond**

If a landlord or manager does not correct a reported problem, tenants may contact:

**Healthy Housing and Vector Control**

**415‑252‑3800**

Assistance is available in multiple languages. Tenants may also call **311**.

**8\. Temporary Relocation**

If health or safety is at serious risk, the Director of Health may require temporary relocation. Tenants must cooperate with DPH and management during this process.

**9\. Commercial Food Businesses**

Businesses must store and remove food waste properly. Poor garbage management can threaten health and may lead to permit suspension or revocation.

# V. RESPONSIBILITIES OF RENTAL PROPERTY OWNERS AND MANAGERS

**1\. Training**

Owners/managers must train their staff on:

• How to recognize pests

• How to inspect units

• Good sanitation practices

• How to prevent pests from entering buildings

• How to handle complaints

• How to safely dispose of infested items

**2\. Investigating Reports**

Owners/managers must investigate tenant reports of pest activity **within 72 hours**.

**3\. Recordkeeping**

Accurate records must be kept for at least **two years** and made available to DPH on request. Records must include:

• All reports of infestations

• All services performed by pest control operators

• Dates inspections occurred

**4\. Hiring Licensed Pest Professionals**

Owners/managers must hire a **licensed Pest Control Operator (PCO)**. Proof of licensing must be provided when requested.

**5\. Garbage Storage and Removal**

Owners/managers must provide enough trash containers and ensure garbage is removed often enough to prevent overflowing. The area must be kept clean and maintained.

**6\. Pest Inspections**

PCOs must perform a complete inspection and determine the type and level of infestation.

**7\. Least‑Toxic Methods**

DPH recommends using the least‑toxic methods first, especially in homes where children or medically vulnerable individuals live.

**8\. Advance Notification to Tenants**

Owners/managers must ensure tenants receive proper written notice before pesticide treatments, following state laws. (See Appendix A.)

**9\. Required Training**

DPH may require owners or managers with repeated violations to complete training on sanitation, pest prevention, and building maintenance.

**10\. Assistance for Tenants Who Cannot Prepare Their Unit**

If a tenant cannot safely prepare their unit due to disability or medical need, owners/managers must contact appropriate support services.

# VI. LICENSED PEST CONTROL OPERATORS (PCOs)

**1\. Licensing**

Only licensed PCOs may apply pesticides. They must show proof of a valid license when asked.

**2\. Full Inspection**

PCOs must conduct a complete inspection, identify the pests, and determine where they are living or breeding.

**3\. Advance Notice**

Before treatment, the PCO must provide written notice to the owner/manager and tenants. (See Appendix A.)

**4\. Instructions for Preparation**

Before treatment begins, the PCO must give clear instructions to owners/managers and tenants about how to prepare units.

**5\. Use of Least‑Toxic Methods**

DPH encourages PCOs to use non‑chemical IPM methods when possible. Gel baits are generally safer than sprays if chemicals must be used.

**6\. Inspect Adjacent Units**

All units next to an infested unit must be inspected — and treated if needed.

**7\. Proper Handling of Pesticides**

PCOs must follow all laws and product label directions when transporting, mixing, applying, or disposing of pesticides.

**8\. Use of Additional Tools**

PCOs may use vacuuming, steam, heat, or freezing methods as appropriate.

**9\. Safe Disposal of Infested Materials**

PCOs must give instructions on safely removing infested furniture or materials so pests do not spread.

